The Proculian view was based upon what is called the regula Catoniana, because it was ascribed to one ol the Catos : ‘regula Catoniana sic definit; quod, si testamenti lacti tempore decessisset testator, inutile toret, id legatum, quandocunque decesserit, non valere' Dig. 34. 7. 1. But this rule did not apply to conditional legacies, whose validity was tested at the fulfilment ol the condition, Dig. 35. 1. 98, or to those which were given ex die: ‘Catoniana regula non pertinet ad ea legata, quorum dies non mortis tempore, sed post aditam cedit heredi· tatem’ Dig. 34. 7. 3.
